name: evasive1
column14: 07:00:12 PMQuote from: dhouse on February 20
column17: I would agree that the claims they are making are astounding. They are talking about eventually using "natural language" that would automatically generate code. I'd really like to see some kind of proof that they have figured this out -  but if they have
column18: it would represent a breakthrough that would be so far beyond anything we've seen that it would extremely strange for them to be wasting their time on a blockchain project like this.Just trying to wrap my head around what you've described. Tell me if I'm way off base with this example:- You have a little robotic dog sitting on your table top (with a built-in mic and the processing power to run this AI).- Just by speaking the words
column20: I want you to do a flip."- It will compute the words
column22: and perform the function/flipI know that this example uses hardware on top of software
column23: but is that an idea of what could happen if everything they're claiming is feasible
column24: or is that too outlandish?right - what does "compute the words" and "generate the code" mean? i mean
column25: let's just think of a simple example. How was facebook built? The code was written by people. Writing code is an extremely complex and technical skill. Developers take the idea of what they wanted facebook to be and they built it.Imagine you could just "describe" facebook and a computer would build it.It's obviously theoretically possible
column26: but don't you see how astonishing such a thing would be? Instead of paying millions of dollars a year to software engineers
column27: google could just tell a computer what it wanted and POOF! the code would be there. I would be VERY careful if you are thinking about investing into this project. Read the whitepaper carefully
column28: everyone. Astounding is right then. I mean
column29: theoretically possible one day. You could consider it some kind of holy grail actually
column30: but I can't even fathom the amount of processing power required let alone data transfer speeds. If an AI could be seamlessly tapped into the internet as we know it
column31: maybe. Such a scenario kind of feels like the singularity would already be upon us. No way we're there yet.'

name: AlexTheGreat
column10: 'This is outrageous;Matrix ICO made made me lose my faith in fair ICO.Yesterday the ICO was canceled and today
column11: in 20 minutes
column12: ICO was sold out with 212 transactions. 18 million raised / 212 =  85 k on average per investor.In other words
column13: the ICO was sold out before it even started with big investors and big mining fees taking over everything;The system is rigged
column14: and I am glad regulation is arising to break this shit because even a classic IPO is more fair than this.Ridiculous.They treat "normal" crypto investor like crap
column15: with no cap investment & no pure contract limitation; this was Ultra Capitalism for this ICO; BlockChain in the worst state.'

name: LumeenaThuwan
column10: 'MATRIX adopts a unique hybrid PoS + PoW consensus mechanism. The PoW is performed in a significantly smaller network of delegates
column11: which are selected with a random distributed voting algorithm. The probability of a node to be selected is proportional to its PoS. The “winner” delegate shares the PoW reward with other nodes in its cluster'
